<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870923-0086 </DOCNO><HL> REVIEW andamp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides:Senators Against SDI</HL><DD> 09/23/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)AEROSPACE (ARO)CONGRESS (CNG) </IN><TEXT>   George Bush yesterday had to cast a tie-breaking vote to defeat Louisiana Democrat Bennett Johnston's attempt to reduce next year's spending request for Star Wars research to $3.7 billion. The current attempt by Senators Johnston, Proxmire, Nunn and Glenn to gut SDI is getting a bit strange. As Democrat Senator Howell Heflin said in the debate: &quot;The Soviet Union has had a very active program for many years. {SDI} is vital to our nation's security.&quot; Indeed, a central goal of Soviet strategic-arms politics is to stop our missile defense program while they develop their own. Why is the United States Senate trying to legislate a policy sought by the Soviet Union and opposed by an American president? </TEXT></DOC>